Add ARIA States, Roles, and Properties to the Date Picker

There’s plenty of work left to do to make the date picker more accessible.

The grid of dates aren’t keyboard reachable or operable since they are marked up with divs.

If you click one with the mouse, it will have a CSS class applied that visually indicates it’s been selected.

However, there’s no programmatic update that would inform people using Assistive Technology of the change.

Here’s what the rendered HTML for a selected date currently looks like:

<!-- Rendered HTML of a selected calendar grid item --> 
<div class="grid-btn currentMonth selected">
	<time date-time="2022-08-13">13</time>
	<span class="icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</div>
<!-- Rendered HTML of a selected calendar grid item --> 
<div class="grid-btn currentMonth selected">
	<time date-time="2022-08-13">13</time>
	<span class="icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
</div>

In the Accessibility pane of DevTools, we can see that there is no ARIA label present and the role is generic for an individual date:

🛠️ Challenge: Implement ARIA Role, State, and Property for Date Picker Grid Items

Your challenge is to increase the accessibility of the dates in the date picker grid. This can be accomplished by working through these three tasks:

  • Each of the dates should be focusable and given a proper ARIA role.
  • An ARIA state should be added that indicates whether or not a date has been chosen.
  • Add an ARIA label property that enables the screen reader to announce the full date instead of just the number shown visually.

Here are some hints to help you get started:

Changes should be made inside the date-grid where the array of days is mapped over to create the individual date buttons.

Read through the ARIA Widget Attributes to find one that would help you indicate if a date has been chosen. The logic to set it as true or false will be similar to how the CSS class is applied.

The Day.js library is used to help generate the calendar grid. It includes lots of formatting options. To create a string with the month and day, you can call dayjs(day.date).format('MMMM D') inside of the map function.

Remember, you can always peek at the answer inside of the exercise2 directory if you get stuck!

🛠 Solution Part 1: Adding an ARIA Role for Keyboard Accessibility

The first step is replacing the divs with button elements.

This will provide an implicit role of button and ensure the elements are focusable and operable by the keyboard.

// components/date-picker/date-picker.js
<div className="date-grid">
  {days.map((day, index) => {
    return <button
      className={[
        'grid-btn',
        day.isBooked ? 'booked' : '',
        day.isCurrentMonth ? 'currentMonth' : '',
        isDaySelected(day) ? 'selected' : ''
      ].join(' ').trim()}
      key={index}
      onClick={() => selectDay(day)}
    >
      <time date-time={day.date}>{day.dayOfMonth}</time>
      <span className="icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
    </button>
  })}
</div>
// components/date-picker/date-picker.js
<div className="date-grid">
  {days.map((day, index) => {
    return <button
      className={[
        'grid-btn',
        day.isBooked ? 'booked' : '',
        day.isCurrentMonth ? 'currentMonth' : '',
        isDaySelected(day) ? 'selected' : ''
      ].join(' ').trim()}
      key={index}
      onClick={() => selectDay(day)}
    >
      <time date-time={day.date}>{day.dayOfMonth}</time>
      <span className="icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
    </button>
  })}
</div>

🛠 Solution Part 2: Adding an ARIA State for Chosen Dates

Reading through the options in the ARIA Widget Attributes, there are a few that seem like they could fit our desired use case of indicating that a date has been selected.

aria-checked

A CampSpots user can choose multiple days to book for their trip, so the [aria-checked state](https://www.w3.org/TR/wai-aria-1.2/#aria-checked) might seem like a good fit. However, according to the specification it goes along with elements with a role of checkbox, option, radio, or switch.

Since we’ve implemented the date picker with buttons, this isn’t the right fit.

aria-selected

The first idea that came to my mind was to use the aria-selected state since the user will be selecting dates. However, once again the specification shows us that this state isn’t meant for buttons. Instead, it’s meant to go along with elements that have a role of gridcell, option, row, or tab.

aria-pressed

According to the specification, the aria-pressed state will toggle between true when it’s activated, then back to false when toggled again. It is also used with the button role, so it looks like this is the best choice for us to try with our date buttons.

However, as always the real test is seeing how it works with Assistive Technology.

Looking at how the styles for a selected button are applied, if calling isDaySelected() with the current day object returns true, the selected class will be added to the classNames string:

// excerpt from the date button classNames
isDaySelected(day) ? 'selected' : ''
// excerpt from the date button classNames
isDaySelected(day) ? 'selected' : ''

We can use similar logic to set the value of the aria-pressed state:

return <button	
				aria-pressed={isDaySelected(day) ? 'true' : 'false'}
				...
return <button	
				aria-pressed={isDaySelected(day) ? 'true' : 'false'}
				...

Adding an ARIA Label for Screen Reader Announcement

When looking at the Accessibility Pane in DevTools for a date button, the information still isn’t very useful.

There’s only the text of the number with no additional context in the accessible name.

As seen earlier when we used the <section> tags, we can use an aria-label to provide additional information to a screen reader.

It would be useful to add a label that at least includes the month and day. But we also could indicate in the label whether or not the day has been selected.

We can do this by using a template literal to create a Month and Day string with some help from Day.js. Then we can add the word “selected” using the same technique we used for the ARIA state.

aria-label={
  `${dayjs(day.date).format('MMMM D')}${isDaySelected(day) ? ' selected' : ''}`
}
aria-label={
  `${dayjs(day.date).format('MMMM D')}${isDaySelected(day) ? ' selected' : ''}`
}

Checking Our Work

All together, the updated date button markup now looks like this:

return <button
      aria-label={
          `${dayjs(day.date).format('MMMM D')}${isDaySelected(day) ? ' selected' : ''}`
      }
      aria-pressed={
          isDaySelected(day) ? 'true' : 'false' 
      }
      className={...}
      key={index}
      onClick={() => selectDay(day)}
  >
      <time date-time={day.date}>{day.dayOfMonth}</time>
      <span className="icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
  </button>
return <button
      aria-label={
          `${dayjs(day.date).format('MMMM D')}${isDaySelected(day) ? ' selected' : ''}`
      }
      aria-pressed={
          isDaySelected(day) ? 'true' : 'false' 
      }
      className={...}
      key={index}
      onClick={() => selectDay(day)}
  >
      <time date-time={day.date}>{day.dayOfMonth}</time>
      <span className="icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
  </button>

When we look at DevTools, we can see that the ARIA labels and states are rendered correctly.

🛠 Challenge: Fix Date Picker Key Markup

At the bottom of the date picker is a key that shows icons for “booked”, “available”, and “selected”. There’s also a “Reserve” button. All of these have been marked up as divs.

Update the markup for this part of the date picker to include semantic elements.

🛠 Solution: Fix Date Picker Key Markup

Since the key lists three different items, we could turn the wrapping div into a <ul> and the inner items to be <li>s.

The unordered list element has an implicit role of list and the items inside it have an implicit role of listitem. This means that we shouldn’t have to add any explicit roles.

Because the items in the list have descriptive names, we don’t need to include an ARIA label. The text content inside each one will be used for the list item.

As we’ve already discussed, swapping the “Reserve” button to use the <button> element also has an implicit role applied.

Here’s how the code looks after implementing the updates:

<ul className="date-key">
  <li className="date-key-item-wrap">
      <span className="date-key-item booked">
          <span className="icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
      </span>
      <span className="date-key-text">Booked</span>
  </li>
  <li className="date-key-item-wrap">
      <span className="date-key-item available">
          <span className="icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
      </span>
      <span className="date-key-text">Available</span>
  </li>
  <li className="date-key-item-wrap">
      <span className="date-key-item selected">
          <span className="icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
      </span>
      <span className="date-key-text">Selected</span>
  </li>
</ul>
<button className="reserve-btn">Reserve</button>
<ul className="date-key">
  <li className="date-key-item-wrap">
      <span className="date-key-item booked">
          <span className="icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
      </span>
      <span className="date-key-text">Booked</span>
  </li>
  <li className="date-key-item-wrap">
      <span className="date-key-item available">
          <span className="icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
      </span>
      <span className="date-key-text">Available</span>
  </li>
  <li className="date-key-item-wrap">
      <span className="date-key-item selected">
          <span className="icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
      </span>
      <span className="date-key-text">Selected</span>
  </li>
</ul>
<button className="reserve-btn">Reserve</button>
